<div id="review_2105287151" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2105287151" />
    <a title="Mervin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/70201548-mervin"><img alt="Mervin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1637301282p2/70201548.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2105287151?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mervin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mervin" href="/user/show/70201548-mervin">Mervin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780446363662" href="/book/show/481069.The_Doomsday_Conspiracy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2105287151" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4916216055625750591">I am not much of a fan of SciFi stories. However, I find spy stories more engaging. Fortunately, Sidney Sheldon’s <i>Doomsday Conspiracy</i> provides us a generous helping of the two and tells us an exciting tale of cover-ups and betrayal. Robert Bellamy, a US intelligence agent, gives us a tour around the world as he tracks down witnesses to an extraordinary event in the Swiss Alps. As the story unfolds, we discover that it is more than extraordinary, as it is handled by obscure powers working in the </span>
  <span id="freeText4916216055625750591" style="display:none">I am not much of a fan of SciFi stories. However, I find spy stories more engaging. Fortunately, Sidney Sheldon’s <i>Doomsday Conspiracy</i> provides us a generous helping of the two and tells us an exciting tale of cover-ups and betrayal. Robert Bellamy, a US intelligence agent, gives us a tour around the world as he tracks down witnesses to an extraordinary event in the Swiss Alps. As the story unfolds, we discover that it is more than extraordinary, as it is handled by obscure powers working in the background along with the world’s intelligence agencies. Soon, Robert founds himself in the position of the witnesses that he hunted down.<br /><br />Perhaps the part I enjoyed most is the ingenuity Robert displayed in his tracking down of witnesses and in evading his adversaries, albeit with some conveniences so as to progress his story. The conspiracy part, with the mysterious board headed by Janus (the symbolism behind name flew past over me, I must admit) also piqued my interest, making me want to read more to know the people who are pulling the strings.<br /><br />However, there are certain parts that I found unnecessary or undeveloped. For instance, I found the involvement of Dustin Thornton, although brief, not necessary in advancing the story. The participation of Monte Banks is not thoroughly explored. Add to that the subplot of the Graceful One, which only provided us minute glimpses to this character. The story suffers from a little deus ex machina near the end. I must say, the ending pales in comparison to the adrenaline rush that we have throughout the story. The twists, however, caught me off guard (again, this one flew past over me).<br /><br />I can’t help but think that <i>Doomsday</i> pushes to the reader certain agendas, one which being emphasized at the end of the novel as a supplement to the reader. I am not much of a fan of such matter but I leave it to the readers though it my not be necessary to delve into it to enjoy the story.<br /><br />If you are a fan of conspiracy theories and thrillers, <i>Doomsday Conspiracy</i> might be the one for you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4916216055625750591" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


